  "prompt": "What will happen to the border between Northern Ireland and Ireland following the Brexit vote?",
  "response": "The Brexit vote, which occurred in June 2016, resulted in the United Kingdom deciding to leave the European Union. This decision has significant implications for the border between Northern Ireland, which is part of the UK, and the Republic of Ireland, which remains an EU member.\n\nKey considerations for the border post-Brexit are:\n\n1. **Avoiding a Hard Border**: One of the main objectives of the Brexit negotiations was to avoid re-establishing a hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland. The Good Friday Agreement of 1998, which helped end the conflict in Northern Ireland, emphasized the need for an open border. Both the UK and EU have committed to ensuring that Brexit does not lead to a hard border with physical infrastructure and customs checks.\n\n2. **The Irish Sea Border**: To avoid a hard border on the island of Ireland, the UK and EU agreed on the Northern Ireland Protocol. This protocol effectively places a border in the Irish Sea for goods moving from Great Britain to Northern Ireland. This means checks and controls are implemented on goods entering Northern Ireland from the rest of the UK to ensure they comply with EU rules.\n\n3. **Political and Economic Impacts**: The Northern Ireland Protocol has been contentious. Unionist communities in Northern Ireland feel it separates them from the rest of the UK, leading to political tensions and opposition from some political parties, such as the Democratic Unionist Party (DUP). There have been ongoing negotiations to address these concerns, but finding a solution that satisfies all parties remains challenging.\n\n4. **Implementation and Adjustments**: The UK and EU continue to negotiate adjustments to the protocol to address practical issues, reduce the bureaucratic burden on businesses, and ease tensions. The ultimate goal is to find a long-term solution that maintains peace and economic stability in the region.\n\nIn summary, post-Brexit, the border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland is intended to remain open and free of physical infrastructure, in line with the commitments made under the Good Friday Agreement. However, the implementation of the Northern Ireland Protocol has introduced new dynamics and tensions that are still being addressed through ongoing negotiations.",
